Welcome to LEGS

   The Laser Electron Gamma-ray Source (LEGS) at Brookhaven National
   Laboratory produces beams of tagged gamma-rays up to 470 MeV by
   backscattering laser light from 2.8 GeV electrons circulating a storage
   ring of the National Synchrotron Light Source at BNL. The gamma-ray
   beam rate reaches up to 6 MHz in a beam spot of 2 cm by 1 cm. The chief
   characteristic which distinguishes the LEGS beam from other sources of
   gamma-rays is its high degree of polarization, typically greater than
   90%. The beam is tagged, with an energy resolution of 5.5 MeV and an
   efficiency of 100%, by detecting the scattered electrons in a
   spectrometer incorporated into the storage ring .
